Introduction¶

In [ ]:
In [ ]:

Domestic flight delays can cost billion dollars to passengers, airlines yearly. Much of this burden along with aggravation comes at the cost of passengers who not only lose time waiting for their planes to leave, but they also miss connecting flights. The question then is, what are the causes for these delays? We are going to analyze combined datasets from the years 2009 to 2018, containing up to 60,000,000 different internal flights in the US. Part One will take on data engineering and review their historical information via data exploration. Part two will continue in another notebook and will use classification models to predict which flights are most likely to arrive late and what are the causes.

AWS EMR-7.0.0 was used for this project. Applications: Hadoop 3.3.6, JupyterEnterpriseGateway 2.6.0, JupyterHub 1.5.0, Livy 0.7.1, Spark 3.5.0, PySpark 3.5

The data sets were downloaded from Kaggle. They can be viewed by going to the following link:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/yuanyuwendymu/airline-delay-and-cancellation-data-2009-2018

Data Review¶

Data Dictionary¶

In [ ]:

CRS-Computer Reservation System ArrDel15-Arrival Delay Indicator, flight arrived 15 Minutes or More past CRS Sheduled Arrival. (0=No, 1=Yes)

DepDel15-Departure Delay Indicator, flight depaerted 15 Minutes or More past CRS scheduled departure time. (0=No, 1=Yes)

OP_CARRIER-Airline carrier code

ORIGIN-Airport flight departed.

CRS_DEP_TIME- Departure Time scheduled by CRS.

DEP_TIME-Actual Departure Time (local time: hhmm) It's important to note that the departure time is the moment a plane pushes back from the gate, not the time it takes off.

DEP_DELAY-Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual departure time. Early departures show negative numbers.

WHEELS_OF-Actual Take-Off Time

WHEELS_On-Actual landing Time

TAXI_OUT-The time elapsed between departure from the origin airport gate and wheels off, in minutes.

TAXI_IN-Taxi time from wheels down to arrival at the gate, in minutes.

CRS_ARR_TIME-Arrival time as scheduled in CRS.

ARR_TIME-Actual Arrival Time (local time: hhmm)

ARR_DELAY-Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual arrival time. Early arrivals show negative numbers.

CANCELLED-Flight Canceled. Indicator (0=No,1=Yes)

DIVERTED-Flight landed at different airport than origianl scheduled airport.

CRS_ELAPSED_TIME-Expected elapsed Time of Flight per CRS, in Minutes

CTUAL_ELAPSED_TIME-Actual Elapsed Time of flight, in Minutes.

AIR_TIME-Flight Time, in Minutes

DISTANCE-Distance between airports (miles)

CARRIER_DELAY-Carrier Delay, in Minutes. Carrier delay is within the control of the air carrier. Examples of occurrences that may determine carrier delay are: aircraft cleaning, aircraft damage, awaiting the arrival of connecting passengers or crew, baggage, bird strike, cargo loading, catering, computer, outage-carrier equipment, crew legality (pilot or attendant rest), damage by hazardous goods, engineering inspection, fueling, handling disabled passengers, late crew, lavatory servicing, maintenance, oversales, potable water servicing, removal of unruly passenger, slow boarding or seating, stowing carry-on baggage, weight and balance delays.

WEATHER_DELAY-Weather Delay, in Minutes. Weather delay is caused by extreme or hazardous weather conditions that are forecasted or manifest themselves on point of departure, enroute, or on point of arrival.

NAS_DELAY-National Air System Delay, in Minutes.Delay that is within the control of the National Airspace System (NAS) may include: non-extreme weather conditions, airport operations, heavy traffic volume, air traffic control, etc. Delays that occur after Actual Gate Out are usually attributed to the NAS and are also reported through OPSNET.

SECURITY_DELAY-Security Delay, in Minutes. Security delay is caused by evacuation of a terminal or concourse, re-boarding of aircraft because of security breach, inoperative screening equipment and/or long lines in excess of 29 minutes at screening areas.

LATE_AIRCRAFT_DELAY-Late Aircraft Delay, in Minutes. Arrival delay at an airport due to the late arrival of the same aircraft at a previous airport. The ripple effect of an earlier delay at downstream airports is referred to as delay propagation.

schDepWhOffDiff-Difference between scheduled departure time and wheels up.

wheOnScArrDiff-Difference between wheels down and scheduled arrival time.

DayOfWeek-1 (Monday) - 7 (Sunday)

DayOfMonth-1-31

Month-1-12

DepartureDelayGroups-Departure Delay intervals, every (15 minutes from <-15 to >180). Negative observations are set to zero.

0 Delay between 0 and 14 minutes 1 Delay between 15 to 29 minutes 2 Delay between 30 to 44 minutes 3 Delay between 45 to 59 minutes 4 Delay between 60 to 74 minutes 5 Delay between 75 to 89 minutes 6 Delay between 90 to 104 minutes 7 Delay between 105 to 119 minutes 8 Delay between 120 to 134 minutes 9 Delay between 135 to 149 minutes 10 Delay between 150 to 164 minutes 11 Delay between 165 to 179 minutes 12 Delay >= 180 minutes

DepTimeBlk-CRS Departure Time Block, Hourly Intervals

1--001-0559 12:00AM to 5:59AM 2--0600-0659 6:00AM to 6:59AM 3--0700-0759 7:00AM to 7:59AM 4--0800-0859 8:00AM to 8:59AM 5--0900-0959 9:00AM to 9:59AM 6--1000-1059 10:00AM to 10:59AM 7--1100-1159 11:00AM to 11:59AM 8--1200-1259 12:00PM to 12:59PM 9--1300-1359 1:00PM to 1:59PM 10--1400-1459 2:00PM to 2:59PM 11--1500-1559 3:00PM to 3:59PM 12--1600-1659 4:00PM to 4:59PM 13--1700-1759 5:00PM to 5:59PM 14--1800-1859 6:00PM to 6:59PM 15--1900-1959 7:00PM to 7:59PM 16--2000-2059 8:00PM to 8:59PM 17--2100-2159 9:00PM to 9:59PM 18--2200-2259 10:00PM to 10:59PM 19--2300-2359 11:00PM to 11:59PM

DistanceGroup-Distance Intervals, every 250 Miles, for Flight Segment

1--Less Than 250 Miles 2--250-499 Miles 3--500-749 Miles 4--750-999 Miles 5--1000-1249 Miles 6--1250-1499 Miles 7--1500-1749 Miles 8--1750-1999 Miles 9--2000-2249 Miles 10--2250-2499 Miles 11--500 Miles and Greater

We will use ARR-DELAY for the creation of a new binary feature in which the codes will be "0"(arrived on time), and "1"(arrived late).

In [33]:
# Define a SQL query to calculate the time difference in minutes
sql_query = """
    SELECT
           idx,
           WHEELS_OFF,
           WHEELS_ON,
           CRS_DEP_TIME,
           CRS_ARR_TIME,
           ABS(CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(CRS_DEP_TIME, 4, '0'), 1, 2) AS INT) * 60 + CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(CRS_DEP_TIME, 4, '0'), 3, 2) AS INT) -
               (CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(WHEELS_OFF, 4, '0'), 1, 2) AS INT) * 60 + CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(WHEELS_OFF, 4, '0'), 3, 2) AS INT))) AS schDepWhOffDiff,
            ABS(CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(CRS_ARR_TIME, 4, '0'), 1, 2) AS INT) * 60 + CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(CRS_ARR_TIME, 4, '0'), 3, 2) AS INT) -
               (CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(WHEELS_ON, 4, '0'), 1, 2) AS INT) * 60 + CAST(SUBSTRING(lpad(WHEELS_ON, 4, '0'), 3, 2) AS INT))) AS wheOnScArrDiff   
    FROM time_table
"""

# Execute the SQL query
result_df = spark.sql(sql_query)

For efficiency, we will create a function that will search the entire data set and produce the number of null values for each feature.

In [ ]:
In [56]:
#missing values check
from pyspark.sql.functions import count, when, isnan, col


def missing_calculation(df, miss_percentage=0.80):
    
    #checks for both NaN and null values
    missing = df.select(*[count(when(isnan(c) | col(c).isNull(), c)).alias(c) for c in df.columns])
    length_df = df.count()
    ## convert to pandas for efficient calculations
    final_missing_df = missing.toPandas().transpose()
    final_missing_df.reset_index(inplace=True) 
    final_missing_df.rename(columns={0:'missing_count'}, inplace=True) 
    final_missing_df['missing_percentage'] = final_missing_df['missing_count']/length_df
    
    #select variables with cardinality of 1
    vars_selected = final_missing_df['index'][final_missing_df['missing_percentage'] >= miss_percentage] 
    
    return final_missing_df

The percentage of flight delays remained consistent with only the years 2013 and 2014 having flight arrival delays greater than twenty percent.

# Calculate the percentage of DepDel15 equal to 1 grouped by Orginating Airport HAVING COUNT(Airline) > 29000



query = """
SELECT
    ORIGIN,
    ROUND((SUM(CASE WHEN DepDel15 = '1' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) / COUNT(*) * 100),2) AS perc_OriginDepDel15
FROM
    data_explore
GROUP BY
    ORIGIN
    
HAVING COUNT(ORIGIN) > 29000  

ORDER BY perc_OriginDepDel15 DESC
"""

We next analyze data for originating airports. Atlanta is on top the greatest percentage of total domestic flights at just over six percent. Chicago and Dallas Fort Worth follow at over four percent of total domestic flights. Airlines at the top of Departure delays are Chicago’s Midway International Airport, Houston, Newark, and Dallas, all with departure delay percentage of twenty three percent or above. Interestingly, two of the airlines at the top, Midway international and Dallas are not the major airports for their respective cities. Viewing the table for average taxi out minutes, JFK, and LaGuardia rank at top with average departure minutes of 27 and 36 respectively. This is interesting as both airports account for around one percent of total flights each. Departure traffic does not seem to be the result of the high taxi out minutes. The tables on weather delays and security delays by airport show there are few effects on delays based on these events. The NAS Average delayed minutes results have Vogue Valley International–Medford Airport, Patrick Leahy Burlington International Airport, San Luis Obispo County Regional Airport, and Eugene Airport With average NAS delayed minutes at 5 minutes or above. These are small airports with less than a tenth of percent of total domestic flights. They do not appear near the top of the other tables for origin airports so it’s interesting that tier average NAS delayed minutes are higher than larger airports.

Our next analysis will be of groups and time blocks.

Departure time block with less than four parent of total flights are. 8:00 pm, 9:00 pm, 10:00pm, 11:00 pm, and 12:00am to 5:59am. These are not surprising due to the lateness or early departing times. The rest are above five percent or above of total flights. The time block departure table has time blocks 6:00pm, 7:00pm, 8:00pm and 9:00pm all with late departures above twenty five percent. Interesting that the are all early evening to later at night. Results from the classification models will hopefully provide a clearer picture on this. Viewing the distance group table, unsurprisingly, distances between 200-499 and 500-749 account for twenty five percent and twenty percent of the total domestic flights respective. Groups less than 250 and 550-999 are fourteen and thirteen percent respectively. All other groups are under ten percent of total flights. In terms of percent of departure delays, there is not large differences. The distance group of 1000-1249 has late departures of nineteen percent whereas distance group less than 250 has a late departure of sixteen percent.
